The architects saw - the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini kindergarten here, with everything that belongs to it: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design employees since last year.
The design and architecture office Arch.Design, from whose studios come a whole series of well-known Brno buildings, calculated from the first designs for the new building Avriopoint with the premises for its company mini-kindergarten.
In wise foresight, because most of his 90 employees are in the baby boom age and the company is anxious that the project owners return to their workplace as soon as possible.
Together with the possibility to work shorter, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer to its employees in the concept of their social program.
It is thus easier for civil engineers and architects to reconcile their demanding profession and child care.
The Minikindergarten is an original idea of Arch.Design's employees and with the support of management, they were able to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The mini-kindergarten is financed by the Human Resources and Employment Policy Operational Programme from the European Social Fund and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this financing (grants of CZK 2,8 million), the necessary facilities and equipment have been procured and for a period of 2 years qualified personnel and operation are provided.
After the funding has been used up (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue to run the Minikindergarten 3 at its own expense for further years.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the processing of applications.
The children are cared for by all-time qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is about a mini kindergarten, only 5 children may be present at the same time, but the day alternates over several children.
The kindergarten business is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in terms of the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although these are individual education and care, the programme content in the Mini-Kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework programme of pre-school education.
The children not only play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to preschool instruction, by the way, they also learn English.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys and creative games, but also with a computer that is available to the children.
What's more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive business environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus eliminate the stress of late picking up the children from a far-away kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working time more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships are also emerging here.
Arch.Design thus joined the Czech companies, which offer clear benefits when recruiting new employees, which are family-friendly and strengthen their personal marketing through such programs.
A bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs such as the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants the house with its organic forms was nicknamed "Knochenhaus."
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tiles and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of sheds and ubiquitous soft lines, all of these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The façade of the house plays with fantastic lines, tender colors and textures that remind of nature and living beings.
It is only on closer inspection that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and well thought-out order.
During the night, the entire façade looks even more sculptural, dramatic and the special illumination enhances the shine of the colors.
The same sweeping lines and winding shapes dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even peepholes and groins.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was built by the reconstruction of a house from 1877, which architect Emilio Sala Cortese carried out.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
However, the apartment house Casa Batlló was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
Especially on its drawing board were the decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner and also the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, numerous other painters and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá in the Park of Güell, where there are also other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given the nickname "Knochenhaus" by the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "yawning house."
It is also said that at the very top of the building the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia, is depicted.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed a central heating system with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces, which was unique for the house at that time.
A little bit bizarre seems to be her 45-degree incline.
In his work Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations at that time and was by no means perplexed by them.
Before construction began, he obtained the relevant building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later the city's fathers were so horrified by the result that they demanded remedy.
Among other things, the Councillors also met with the fact that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, there were no changes, quite the contrary - only fifteen days after the request of the district, Josep Batlló submitted a request for the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a parlour, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
By the basic elements of the conversion all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and thus a larger society could comfortably chat without having to renounce a certain intimacy in confidential conversations.
In addition to a new façade, Gaudí's renovation also provided the house with a rather unusual roof and two further floors.
Gaudí's play with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is disguised and the courtyards of light are also impressive.
The play of these two colours gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
He simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb sunlight on the contrary.
The house Casa Batlló, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can now be visited by anyone.
On the first floor is the most spacious and magnificent apartment made accessible to the public.
The homeowners only decided in the year to take this step and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was discovered that this was a fairly profitable business, the tours were retained, and they were extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price to visit the monument is not a cardboard handle, it amounts to 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards receive 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
Those who want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers should try to make friends with one of the house dwellers and visit him at home.
The right mattress and the right bed rust? Women have different desires than men
Not the greatest bed frame, but the quality of the lying area - so mattress and rust make up the good bed.
However, these must complement each other harmoniously in order to meet the wishes of the specific user.
Many things play a role in the selection - the weight, the size, the health status and, last but not least, the sex of the sleeper.
Just as important is the interior, in which mattress and rust have to subordinate themselves.
Typical example?
Latex mattresses are not well suited in a weekend home that does not heat regularly, as they need much longer to "get warm."
In addition, they are significantly heavier than usual polyurethane mattresses.
And - they should be turned on a regular basis.
If they don't have enough ventilation canals in the core and are also lying on a solid plate, moisture gets wet: It is therefore not excluded that it forms under their mold.
Of course, what you are used to also plays a role in the election.
Those who have been abroad for a long time, where very high mattresses with a soft layer are common, will be hard to get used to a low mattress with a hard surface.
"Well, all the ice hockey players who came back from the NHL complained to me that they couldn't sleep properly here anymore."
"For their worn shoulders, heels and hips, they simply need a soft layer of visco foam (Memory Foam - a shape memory polymer)."
