"Today this is no longer a problem, because such mattresses offer among others the manufacturer Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex or the Czech manufacturer Tropico."
And you don't have to be a famous hockey player to appreciate the benefits of the Visco Foam.
This "miracle" actually works quite simply.
The foam optimalizes its hardness and shape according to the absorbed heat, in other words, it really nestles on the warm body.
Nowhere does it press, in the night you don't roll around like after a heavy fight.
You just sleep a lot better.
The viscoelastic foam also provides protection against decubitus.
When choosing the size of the mattress, you should still calculate the length of the soles of your feet, i.e. about 21 to 34 cm.
Man and woman, who are 180 cm tall, need a 210 to 220 cm long bed.
Each of the sleepers should have at least 90 cm of lying width available, i.e. 180 cm together.
For single beds, for example for singles, 120 to 140 cm are attached.
For convenience and also for possible visitors.
Otherwise, the following rule of thumb applies to the ideal width of the bed: "If you lie on your back, there should still be enough room for the slightly angled arms," advises Ing. Helena Prokomová, the guild master of the upholsterer and room outfitter, who has been devoted to the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture for years and also presents this topic at technical schools.
With a double bed, everyone needs their own rust and mattress, but be careful when shopping, so that the mattresses are equally high.
Otherwise, there is no choice but to mount the grates at different heights and that is by no means possible with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, mattresses with a feather skeleton should be 15 cm, of which at least three centimetres should be on the mould layer and the fine padding.
"With your hand or when you sit down, you must not feel the feathers," warns Helena Prokomová.
Each mattress requires a special rust type.
Fully upholstered beds with mattress and base like grown-up Siamzwillinge have nothing to do in the bedroom.
These mattresses cannot be ventilated and the cover cannot be washed, which is already common today.
And since you lose between 0.2 and 0.75 l of sweat in a single night, it is clear that after five to seven years the mattress slowly becomes a huge (and clogged sieve).
This is also why experts reject advertising slogans that promise a lifespan of up to 25 years, even lifelong warranty for mattresses.
Every thing has its ifs and buts.
And therefore a practical advice from the dealers: For mattresses of 120 or 140 cm width one should not shy away the hygiene of the washable, removable covers, nevertheless it is recommended to use a mattress protector, which one can easily remove and wash.
