Local manufacturers use, for example, the foams Eucatherm C, Twinsaver or similar products.
More and more parents want human monitoring devices to keep the kids under control
The fear of one's own children is growing and so more and more parents are considering monitoring them via GPS.
The system, which was originally invented to search for cars, can also locate people, which would also be helpful in such cases, as in the recent disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette box, but soon it should not be larger than a watch.
Many people have put the case of the disappeared Anička in fear and terror, so they look for ways and means to protect their children better.
Also for the price of impairing their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not about spying, but about an effective means of reducing the likelihood of tragedy," says Petr Pilin from Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that in individual cases such devices can be misused, for example if you put it in someone's pocket without knowing about it, but we haven't had a case like this."
"Most customers really buy it for security reasons," Pilin adds.
In his opinion, however, the child should always know the purpose of the "box " and how to use it in an emergency.
However, child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child doesn't like to wear such a thing, he simply gets rid of it.
"Even very small children show great creativity when it comes to deliberately losing certain things if they do not want to be controlled."
"Even the mobile phones at first aroused great expectations with the parents, but they can be switched off just as easily as these new surveillance devices," says Ms. Bočková.
In their opinion, it is also controversial whether such an institution actually helps in the event of an attack.
