Maestro gelating Luciano Ferrari first explains to the participants the ideal properties of the perfect ice cream.
The decisive factor is not only good taste, but also silky suppleness and good consistency.
Luciano doesn't forget the icing of the national and even southern superstructure during his training: "Italian Gelato is simply the best - and then there is a lot of romance."
The first step to manufacturing seems quite simple.
Luciano tips the basic ingredients milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and stabilizers into a large mixing device that heats everything up to 85 degrees with an electronic program and then immediately cools it down to four degrees.
Then he turns a tap on the machine and comes out a pasteurized white base cream, basis for all milk ice cream varieties.
The lecturer is immediately stormed with questions: Can ice cream only be produced with natural substances without stabilizers?
How can you let your own desire for experimentation run wild?
Luciano warns against being misled by the zeitgeist.
Those who speak of ice cream "only from natural ingredients" may have used stabilizers - usually a natural product, such as guar gum from the guar bean.
Of course you can make ice even without a stabilizer, only then it has to be sold within a day, otherwise it will fall into itself, and the customer bites on no ice cream.
Certain variations on the base mass are allowed.
It becomes more exciting with the aromas.
For the taste in the ice, Maestro Luciano distinguishes between the ingredients you buy in the fruit department or in the sweets of the supermarket.
There are also powders and pastes.
"The suppliers will all try to turn on you dozens of flavored additives."
"But you should just experiment."
Either with the fruit orbets with sugar and fresh fruits.
Or just with the ice cream from the white base mass, which becomes a yellow cream with eggs and with cocoa powder as the basis for all possible chocolate seductions.
Now the students are allowed to use the ice machines.
Luciano makes four different types of vanilla, chocolate, mocha and hazelnut ice cream - with or without eggs in the base mass, with more or less vanilla aroma or other natural additives.
The fruit ice varieties are also subjected to the same experiment.
More flavors, more fruit puree - this is not necessarily better taste.
Hazelnut ice cream does not necessarily taste more nutty when it contains more hazelnuts.
The most popular kiwi ice makes the working group that uses more fruits, less water and a little less stabilizer.
Only a balanced mixture correctly enhances the taste of a gelato, says Luciano.
Ice production is a calculation task: If peach puree is used with a lot of sugar, the sugar content in the basic recipe must be reduced.
An extra portion of sugar is needed for lemon ice cream.
Luciano draws out a device by which he determines the sugar content of the fruit varieties (Winzer thus measure the Oechsle in grape must).
Fortunately, tables facilitate computing.
Making ice cream doesn't require as much physical use as it used to be.
Not only does the device help for the automatic production of the base mass.
There is also a device in which the finished ice mixture is beaten creamy at the same time and cooled to minus temperatures.
Despite all automation, small breakdowns are not possible.
The Brazilian Gustavo clings to himself and his classmates from top to bottom with fruit puree when the oversized rod mixer gets out of his control.
"In every course," says Maestro Luciano, "it's just a matter of time before something like this happens."
