The democracy movement in Latin America is becoming stronger, as is the support of private companies.
Crime is a greater problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, Brazil's influence is greater than that of the United States.
These were the results of the Latinobarómetro survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been carried out regularly since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly striking in this year's survey of September and October.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased strongly (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has been growing by about 6% a year since 2002, the number of supporters of democracy has risen from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
This trend can also be seen in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since the sharp fall last year.
But only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Chart 2).
About 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country's democratic practice, which is as much as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Diagram 3).
About 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% of their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crises undermined efforts to increase democracy.
This continued during the global economic crisis, perhaps because the countries of Latin America experienced only a short period of recession and recovered quickly.
In addition, the poor were caught up by a stronger social network.
(According to reports from the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and fell again by 32% this year.)
However, there are strong differences in mood from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widespread sense of progress.
This is less the case in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more severe and violence has increased.
Only for the second time since the start of the survey do many people in Latin America see crime in their country as a major problem than unemployment (see Chart 5).
About 31% say that either she or a family member were victims of a crime last year, but compared to 38% last year, the figures have dropped and thus reached the lowest level since 1995.
The rise in economic performance is reflected in the increased support for the private and market economies: around 71% of respondents across the region indicated that the private sector is essential for development, in 2007 it was 56% (see Chart 6).
