Zapatero and the red line of Germany
Berlin has decided to retain the euro, but at the same time has set conditions for the entire European Union.
The tensions in the markets have triggered a double response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has put forward new adaptation measures, ranging from tax reductions for small and micro enterprises, regulation of temporary employment companies or the lifting of the EUR 426 support for unemployed people who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatisation of 49 percent of AENA, the administration of Barajas and El Prat airports, and 30 percent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, with the help of former President Felipe González, the deputy head of government, Elena Salgado, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as responsible for the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It is anticipated that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany takes a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which conflicts with the maintenance of the traditional traditions of a large part of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: The re-establishment of the German mark - although this currently sounds more like science fiction - supported by a large proportion of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a redesign of the euro according to German proposals. This means: more macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of countries that exceed the requirements; possibly the cessation of payments of some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been emerging for some time now, so there are no excuses.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government pulled a constitutional reform out of its sleeve to prevent this from happening in 2016.
This was the first sign of the drift between what Germany thought necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was the Central European country, when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to save Greece.
At that time this was strongly criticized, but the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, public opinion and public opinion were absolutely against a rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last few days of October, Merkel has once again come out with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union's agreements in order to enable a country to be rescued and, at the same time, to oblige private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it drives forward the Irish crisis and everything that follows.
But their proposal, albeit somewhat sweetened, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will be participating in the reform of the European Union, which will enable these measures to take place from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line which it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that, even if unpopular measures have to be taken now, the old functioning of the euro will no longer exist from this date.
2013 will be the year of the birth of a new currency area, in which the countries that are opposed to it will be severely punished, forced to declare themselves insolvent and, in this case, the private sector will have to cover part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we need to pursue a tough growth path, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as Spain cited in boom times, will simply not be acceptable.
The offer is clear.
And we would do bad not to understand.
It's not just about reducing the government deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is cheat on ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will be more calm.
And that we will make use of the opportunities offered by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero has also understood this, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures of yesterday) points out that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in the home has paved its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn't look like something would change.
Among the possibilities envisaged, the fact that we would have to leave the euro area full of little serious countries is not to be ruled out.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sports and regulation bypass
Tricks like those by Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventive spirit, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The alleged exclusion of two players from the Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match of November 23 against the Ajax in the Champions League resulted in a lot of ink being shed about whether or not it was an unsporty action and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since the Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will comply with the prescribed penalty in the next league match against the Auxerre, thus entering the next game phase without playing cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules that have been followed in this sport.
Part of the upcoming debate about the presented case is that a team of the football club Real Madrid (who in his anthem pretended elegance and honor and on other occasions punished his players for similar incidents) played the main role, and the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long story as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this practice, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these acts constitute a rule-breaking. Indeed, this procedure adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused to the spirit of sport should be investigated.
The sport spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid the opposing players taking undue advantage of the counterteam, either.
The paradox of the action of Real Madrid's players is that it does not correspond to what we normally mean by misplay or bypassing rules, because the circumvention of the rule was not carried out secretly to avoid a sanction, but rather should be as conspicuous as possible in order to punish it by the referee.
The players waited and accepted the penalty joyfully.
Another question is what kind of advantage did the objectors draw from the intentional fouls.
It should be pointed out here that the rival was not put in a less favorable position, nor were benefits for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next game phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term advantage, which is uncertain up to a certain degree, as the team could eventually withdraw. In addition, players receive a penalty with this approach and pass into the second card cycle, in which they withdraw less because of card accumulation with one card than in the first cycle.
This does not make it so clear whether it really is an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sport, which includes strategic decisions to maximise the benefits of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent a sanction (that would actually be a clear case of rule bypass), they wanted to choose when they would be subject to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or escaping punishment.
Although the boundary between invention and the rule environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of invention.
I have the impression that the polemic has arisen as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked transmission of rules.
The damage caused by these actions to the principles of sport is less ethical than rather aesthetic.
