China maintains its greenhouse gas reduction targets
At COP16, China's representative said that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and that it would maintain its offer to reduce 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China keeps its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, says Su Wei, the country's representative at COP16.
During his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations Climate Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and transform its industry.
He said that in the last four years his country has invested $245 million to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its objectives, but would work together with the international community on this matter.
He explained that the Chinese climate change strategy is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
He explained that progress had been made in all aspects, including the adoption of a new energy law last year, which contained the objectives of reducing the emission of gases.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, state authorities had cooperated with central government and local authorities to achieve energy saving, effective use of energy and emission reduction targets.
He also stated that some multi-annual plans have already been launched or finalised, both those financed by the Chinese Government and those received from other countries.
For example, he referred to the effective use of energy programme, which has been introduced over the past five years and which has received investment from the United Nations (UNO), the government and private sector.
There is also a project at provincial level on climate change, another on the exchange of traditional light bulbs by energy-saving bulbs and another on mitigation and adaptation, he explained.
Martin Krol, scientific government advisor on climate change in this country, confirmed that China's efforts were far greater than was commonly thought.
He pointed out that per capita emissions of greenhouse gases in China amount to six tonnes per person, while in the United States they are 100 tonnes. China is responsible for a nine percent total contribution to pollution.
It is also making unprecedented progress in the field of energy use. Energy efficiency has been increased by 20 percent over the last five years and another step is to be taken by 2020, he said.
