But the advocates of the law need sixty votes to adopt the initiative, which is why they depend on the voices of a handful of Republicans. Currently, the organizations of the advocates of this project are organizing an intensive influence on the adoption of the law.
The Democrats, of whom the majority support the Dream Act, have 58 seats.
However, one of them said that the senator Ben Nelson from Nebraska would vote against and only one Republican, Richard Lugar from Indiana, has announced his support of the law.
Therefore, the defenders of the Dream Act must have several Republicans on their side if other Democrats decide to turn their backs on the initiative.
Among the most popular Republicans are those from Maine, Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins, as well as Senator George Lemieux from Florida, who took over the mandate of senator Mel Martínez.
Other Republicans who have supported the Dream Act in the past are Orrin Hatch from Utah and Kay Bailey Hutchinson from Texas, but they said they would not support it on another occasion.
Another Republican who had voted in favour of the law, John McCain, has not yet established his position.
Although the House of Representatives has a different version, the analysts agree that the Dream Act in the Senate is facing the biggest obstacles.
Put your finger in the wound with literature
The second round of 'The Lust of Language' was a walk in which the participants made a strong contribution to the story.
"I understand the thing about sex in the language, but... the finger in the wound? What is expected of me?" asked the writer Luisa Valenzuela, who was to open the second round of 'Los placeres de la lengua', a cycle that celebrated Spanish-language literature and used the subtitle of her question on this occasion (at another event, the round table was devoted to sex in the language, she explained).
The finger in the wound... "brings us in trouble," the Argentine scripture sweetly spit at the audience, which consisted mainly of young people who met at the International Book Fair in Guadalajara (FIL) to attend this round table hosted by Marisol Shultz, attended by Valenzuela, Sergio Ramírez, Mayra Montero and Luis García Montero.
Luisa Valenzuela read a text she dedicated to Gonzalo Celorio, and then characterized the Shultz as a great story. Luisa tells in the first person and is the protagonist who is looking to know what a "wound" is and goes from doctor to doctor, from whom she receives no answer, but hints for the guide to her story.
She leaves the infectologist convinced: "Patience is not my strength, perhaps it is my wound."
Finally, after a frustrating approach to the traumatologist, who took her breath away in the middle of the passage, and who explains to her that wound is not a scientific term, the psychoanalyst reveals the secret: "the wound is really open, the symbolic is the scar."
The main character of the story sighs with relief and closes that she "only learned from the wound that it is really open and does not exist." But she is convinced that the lust for language and its traps mix.
Valenzuela, the writer, played with both of them.
The Nicaraguan Sergio Ramírez also presented a delightful narrative, which he called 'Lob of Invention', in which the finger in the wound is not mentioned, but discovered.
With allusions to magic realism, he tells of a famous sorceress who touched the clouds, brought back far-traveled men or restored the virtue lost by a girl. The story made a turnaround and told of America, the great novel that had not been lacking in his own chroniclers from the beginning, and he quoted Bernal Díaz del Castillo, who criticized the abundance of stories told by the conquerors.
"Cervantes, who invited us all (the writers), mocked the fake witnesses who appeared in the stories depicted as true, but in other ways the story of America would never have been told - with imagination, which even lost the sense of shame."
However, he emphasizes that "it is the crazy and liar who best imagines things," and that is where reality and lies approach each other, where one no longer knows which side the narrative belongs to, where fictional literature reaches the summit.
He actually calls this the 'Tradition Cervantes'.
"We inherited from him to be what is told."
When it was Mayra Montero's turn, the writer commented and praised the variety of interpretations to which FIL's invitation to the Round Table 'The Finger in the Wound' had contributed.
The Cuban and Puerto Rican woman dedicated her contribution to the great wound of social violence that affects her country - like all of Latin America - as a result of the struggles for drug trafficking.
"I believe that good literature, good poetry, good songs contain an implicit, not deliberately planned commitment," she explained after emphasising that literature is communication and commitment that builds between the author and the readers as if it were a "chemical reaction."
The evening was decided by the Spanish poet Luis García Montero, whose contribution also hevorob raised "this finger of the dedicated writer in the wound of the writer."
He noted that in a fast-paced world the intellectual habits and control of consciousness also lead to dogmatisms, and will forget "that behind every confirmation is a little no and behind every denial a little yes."
"To be in possession of our thoughts and reality, we need to nuance: and nuance often means putting the finger in the wound and harassing those who feel much more comfortable when they think in the form of cartoons, in black and white, in prefabricated ideas without nuances, and also harassing the powerful who prefer to divide the world into black and white, he noticed and invited to rediscover the meaning of writing.
Romano fights for his first title
Rubén Omar Romano looks back on three defeats in finals, he has experienced ups and downs in his career, but three times he played decisive games.
The duel between Santos Laguna and Monterrey at the end of the game also contrasts with two different styles set by their respective coaches, and their encounter, marked by opposites, is reflected in the results.
Rubén Omar Romano looks back on three defeats in finals, he has experienced ups and downs in his career, but three times he has had decisive games, and so far he has kept himself well, which is why this opportunity is of particular importance to him.
The Argentine has played high with the medal to the second champion, he has left one step behind the winners and surprisingly he has played consecutive finals with the same team.
The santistic strategist reached the first final as a coach at the 'Torneo Apertura 2002', when del Morelia had the reins in his hand, with which he had a big defeat against Toluca with 4-2; later, at the 'Clausura 2003' he achieved the decisive duel, which he also lost with 3-1 against Rayados.
Already with Santos Laguna on the 'Torneo Bicentenario 2010', in which they played against Los Diablos, Rubén had to take a setback again, because the game with 2-2 against Los Choriceros went out in a draw after 210 minutes, but at the penalty he came forward with 3-1 and got two ways to insert his title, but ultimately three of his players missed the eleven steps and the game turned to a 4-3.
Rubén had already lost two finals with the Diablos Rojos and one with Monterrey, his great rival. Therefore, he does not want to be followed by misfortune and free himself from the evil spell in order to celebrate a title for the first time, although he affirms that the most important thing for him is the game itself.
"I want to be a champion, I don't want to break statistics, that's for a club, for my affection, and that's why the title will come to me, but what happens before is the most important thing," commented the helmsman when asked about the lost finals.
The last final game remained in his memory, he assured that he learned a lot from it: "The only lesson we can learn from it is that until the referee doesn't whistle the end, we can't celebrate, we are prepared on the line, the players are prepared, too, because the last time we were already prepared to leave with two penalty points, and I believe that this is a lesson until the game isn't finished, there is no reason to celebrate."
Knowing that this series could be decided by penalty shooting doesn't worry him, because he trusts his players: "You never want to arrive at penalty shooting, you want to finish in the regular season, but sometimes there is no alternative and you have to be prepared for it, in the previous tour we were prepared, but unfortunately fate prepared us a bad game, sometimes as a result of nervousness or the intense effort to hold the title in our hands, which left us something for this final game, and we hope it won't happen this time."
It is in Romanso's power to be no longer just a second champion and to taste for the first time the fame the titles bring with them.
The US amends the rules for obtaining a visa
Before talking to the consulate, people must introduce themselves to the services for visa applications; costs will be reduced.
From 10 January 2011 the procedures for applying for a visa in the Embassy of the United States and consulates will change.
In the new procedure, most applicants will have to present themselves to the visa application services (ASC, the initial letters in English) before talking to the consulate.
The personnel of the ASC shall record the biometric data of the applicant, which shall be verified by the consulate prior to the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa is reduced, as it is no longer necessary to pay for the appointment, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed over separately.
The applicant shall pay only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the counterweight to 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for hands and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not have to have a conversation at the consulate, they only have to imagine at the nearest ASC, where they submit their documents and their fingerprints are taken.
Since biometric data are collected in the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the conversation at the consulate remain there less time than before.
Those who apply for a visa in the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo no longer have to pay the service premium of $26.
Further information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
NASA Announces the Find of Alien Life
The North American Space Agency called a press conference to present tomorrow a discovery that will have an impact on the search for living beings in space.
The National Aerospace Agency (NASA) of the United States announces tomorrow, Thursday, an astrobiological discovery that could confirm the theory of the existence of alien life.
The discovery will be presented tomorrow at 1 p.m. at a press conference at NASA's headquarters in Washington by experts in astrobiology, a science that examines the origin, development, distribution and future of life in the universe.
When the press conference was convened, NASA assured that it would present "an exciting find for the search for extraterrestrial life," which triggered speculation among experts from other countries.
The discovery could prove the theory that in hostile environments thought to be uninhabitable, it could exist human-like creatures. It was suggested that these could turn into intelligent beings - like humans - if their living conditions improved.
Apparently, it's a microbe found at the bottom of Mono Lake in Yosemite National Park, California, where it lives in an environment thought to be too toxic to all imaginable forms of life, as the lake is highly arsenal.
In some way, the microbe uses arsenic as a survival resource. Taking into account this ability, the chances are that there might be similar lives on other planets that do not have our protective atmosphere.
When these organisms metabolize arsenic, according to the astrobiologists, it is proven that "there is actually a different life form, a second life form that differs from the one we know."
The Space Agency will announce the actual reach of its find at the press conference tomorrow, Thursday.
The conference will be attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who examines the possibility of life on Mars, and biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists studying Titan (the largest moon of Saturn) under the question of whether its chemical composition resembles that of Earth.
