The first decision was taken following a complaint lodged by the "Front commun des personnes assistées sociales du Québec."
The activist organisation had complained that the amounts mentioned in the broadcast were inaccurate.
The moderators should rather provide solid information rather than misleading information.
On the subject of suicide, moderator Stéphane Dupont had argued that suicide was an expression of cowardice.
The majority of Supervisory Board members had concluded that the message conveyed was that suicide should not be seen as a solution to life crises.
"The majority of the Supervisory Board takes into account that the likely consequences of the Dupont le midi programme would have raised a sensitive issue in a family-friendly and appropriate manner."
Therefore, he was not blamed at all for his person.
The last issue concerned the statements relating to the earthquake in Haiti.
In this respect, Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort had delivered a media-effective argument that caused a lot of reactions.
