Worldwide plan for the renewal of lighting
Yesterday in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas (CFCs), which corresponds to almost one third of the additional reduction that needs to be achieved in order to stabilise the Earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete large-scale projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of compelling reduction commitments from industrialised countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem would be avoided in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFCs emitted on the ground due to lighting if white-glowing pears, which are still a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or better still, light emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, had committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, this balance would still have to be deducted from 5 Gt in order to stabilise the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today until 2020 in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white-glowing pears 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by 75%, and with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced twice as much.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last on average between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company, by the way, participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a whitening pear, which conveys an indication of the savings of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that these completely new bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a control resistance.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves, because they contain mercury and therefore they have to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, except for producers who provide a reception point.
However, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet, according to the report, is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit much more mercury in order to generate the electricity wasted by the white-blooded pears.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would generate thanks to this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in purchasing electricity and eight million tonnes of CO2, an equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, the construction of which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
