Ravenish hackers and busy spies
The Affaire WikiLeaks has two meanings.
On one side, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal in the sense of hypocrisy that governs the relations between the states, the citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at international level and gives a foretaste of the future dominated by regression.
But let's go one after the other.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (an x-any nation) is composed exclusively of newspaper clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits throw away nothing but what has been read for months anyway in every random journal (except those whose owner is Berlusconi), and the terrifyingly caricaturated profile of Gaddafi's has long offered cabaret artists material for their sketches.
The rule that the secret files may consist of only known news is essential for the dynamics of the intelligence services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a library dedicated to esotherical publications, you will realize that every work (via the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rosicreuzler) repeats exactly what has already been written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (or because he does not know where to find news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe in nothing other than what they already know and confirm, what they have already learned.
This is also the success mechanism of Dan Brown.
Just like the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited mind) is also the chief of the secret service (otherwise he could be whatever, for example editor at Libération), who considers only what he acknowledges to be true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi, which the American Embassy in Rome had sent to the State Department, was the same as that Newsweek had already published the week before.
So why has such a fuss been made about the revelations of these dossiers?
On one side they say what every educated person already knows, namely that the messages - at least since the end of the Second World War and since then the heads of government can call each other or take an airplane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some small representation tasks, have turned into spy centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy that one does so to ignore it.
Nevertheless, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the task of hypocrisy and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that an arbitrary hacker can tap into the secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world carries a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
In addition, the scandal brings less the victims, rather than the " executioners" into trouble.
But let us dedicate ourselves to the profound nature of what happened.
Formerly, in Orwell's time, all power could be combined like a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy could have turned out to be perfectly correct since then, where you can control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the chosen highway and so on; the citizen would become a total victim of the eye of power.
However, if one considers what is going on today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the control course ceases to be one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - chosen as the avenger of the citizen - can discover the secrets of power.
But how can a power hold itself that is no longer able to keep its own secrets?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is basically a secret free from secrets, since it reveals the public sphere; but in the style of WikiLeaks, revealing that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to deprive them of all power.
WikiLeaks didn't do Sarkozy or Merkel wrong, but Clinton and Obama did.
What will be the consequences of this insult that has been inflicted on such a tremendous power?
It is obvious that in the future, the states will no longer provide any reserved information online - that would be like an outpost glued to the street corner.
But it is equally obvious that with the current technologies it is in vain to hope to keep confidential reports on the phone secret.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state moved on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How could private relationships be maintained in the future, only for certain ears?
I know very well that my prediction at the moment sounds like science fiction and romantic, but I see myself forced to imagine the government agents moving in a secret way diligently on uncontrollable marching routes, carrying their communications nowhere else than in mere memory, and also hiding the few written information they have received in the shoe sales.
The information would be stored in a single copy in closed drawers: basically Watergate's espionage attempt had less success than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is progressing like cancer these days, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communication, the Internet reconstructs a telegraph with (telephone) wire.
The (analogue) video cassettes had enabled the film researchers to explore a film tape by tape, by rewinding from the back to the front and revealing all the secrets of assembly, while the (numerical) CDs nowadays allow nothing but to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. in macro portions.
High-speed trains run from Rome to Milan within three hours, while it takes three and a half hours by plane including the transfer.
It is therefore not unusual for politics and communication technology to return to cars and horses.
One last observation.
In earlier times the press tried to understand what secrets were forged between the messages.
At present, it is the messages that call for confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France talks about its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine compliance with the rapidly resolved financing promises (also called "fast start" or "premature financing") implemented by developing countries.
And already the rough French fairy tales are uncovered.
With the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries have committed themselves to providing 30 billion dollars between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has promised 7.2 billion euros over three years, France 1.26 billion euros (i.e. 420 million per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU has drawn all registers to convince its partners of the fact that they are committed to fast-start financing: detailed action report from its Member States, press conference, major side events, brochure distribution.
The transparency operation is remarkable and especially appreciated for its true value: developing countries and civil society would like to see all developed countries do the same at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2.2 billion euros in 2010, leading it on the right track to pay respect for its 7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But when you look into the details, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be "new and additional" in order to ensure that an additional commitment has been made without being detrimental to public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain member states, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the benchmark they consider best.
For example, the EU Commission has chosen as the benchmark for 2009: international financing will be maintained and will add 150 million for three years under the "Fast Start" financing.
Other countries have adopted similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or in terms of conditions at the level of official development aid.
In return, France felt that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 was "new and additional."
In other words, there are no benchmarks in the expenditure of the previous year or at the global level of official development aid.
In concrete terms, the total amount of French support for developing countries can remain stable (or decrease) - France states that it is committed to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule about this, and everyone chooses their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, have 1 borrowed € equivalent to 1 donated €.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain profitable investments (often linked to emission reduction projects based on the most effective technology), it is deceptive to present the euro, which is to be taken as an equivalent for a donated euro... In addition, only the cost of the loan to the investor country should be counted as a commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing other than the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by borrowing 91.5% (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5%) 36.1 million euros - see also the EU document to convince itself of this.
France is the only country in the EU to use loans to a large extent.
Germany demands 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among other things) pursue 100% of their commitments with donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 on fulfilling its obligations, France is giving just 10 cents and means a comparable use.
Beautiful hocuspocus!
All in all, in its fast-start financing, France operates with a double fraud: partly with a further development of the action over time and partly with the reality of the financial commitment.
France manages to make it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" million in accordance with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could have a double negative effect; once internal to the EU (why do the other member states continue with the donation if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not completely deceived...
The chapter on early financing is only a small question for a relatively short time compared to the whole of discussions on the climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
However, it is essential to learn its lesson from this first year of early financing.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its accounting method for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, however, France could bring forward discussions on the subject of long-term financing (another issue that is crucial and currently under discussion): one cannot escape the question of "predictability" or the way in which its loans are recorded.
France could change its position in order to be as progressive in terms of the issues involved as it is in other matters.
The hope is therefore based on the new Environment Minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about France's fast-start and its vision of "predictability" and the use of loans would naturally raise the international trust base needed for further discussions.
